  "prompt_text": "Prove that the square root of 2 is irrational.",
  "response_text": "To prove that the square root of 2 is irrational, we will use a proof by contradiction. Let's assume that √2 is rational. This means that it can be expressed as a fraction \\( \\frac{a}{b} \\) where \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) are integers with no common factors other than 1 (i.e., the fraction is in its simplest form), and \\( b \\neq 0 \\).\n\nStarting from the assumption:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt{2} = \\frac{a}{b} \\]\n\nWe can square both sides to get:\n\n\\[ 2 = \\frac{a^2}{b^2} \\]\n\nMultiplying both sides by \\( b^2 \\) gives us:\n\n\\[ 2b^2 = a^2 \\]\n\nThis equation tells us that \\( a^2 \\) is an even number because it is equal to \\( 2b^2 \\). Since \\( a^2 \\) is even, \\( a \\) must also be even (the square of an odd number is always odd). Therefore, we can write \\( a \\) as \\( 2k \\) for some integer \\( k \\).\n\nSubstituting \\( a = 2k \\) into the equation \\( 2b^2 = a^2 \\):\n\n\\[ 2b^2 = (2k)^2 \\]\n\\[ 2b^2 = 4k^2 \\]\n\\[ b^2 = 2k^2 \\]\n\nThis equation tells us that \\( b^2 \\) is also even, and thus \\( b \\) must be even as well. However, if both \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) are even, they share a common factor of 2, which contradicts our initial assumption that \\( \\frac{a}{b} \\) is in its simplest form.\n\nSince our assumption that √2 is rational leads to a contradiction, we conclude that √2 must be irrational.\n\n---\n\nVCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 6\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
